Date:    Wed, 22 Sep 93 10:55:51 -0400
From:    padgett@tccslr.dnet.mmc.com (A. Padgett Peterson)
Subject: Silly Season

With the onset of yet another school year, we are seeing another surge
in infections. The strange part is that the BIOS viruses are by far
leading the file infectors.

Meanwhile certain official types seem to have a new headache, the
SATAN-BUG.  Naturally, just to be contrary, this is a file infector.
However, like the 4096 which may have inspired the S-BUG author, it is
very easy to detect when resident as at least (haven't pulled it
completely apart yet) 3k is stolen from the TOM. Unlike the 4096
though the BIOS value is changed along with the MCB so memory checks
match but are low.

Like the 4096, the S-Bug's first target is COMMAND.COM so the first
sign of an infection might be an "invalid COMMAND.COM" warning that
will disappear on reboot. LANs which redirect the COMSPEC will also
crash infected machines unless the LAN copy also becomes infected. In
this case the virus will spread like wildfire (Note: good sanitary LAN
protection practices with read-only and execute-only rights rigorously
maintained will be safe).

Also similar to the 4096, Scanning with a scanner that does not
recognize S-Bug will serve to spread the infection everywhere. S-Bug
also uses multiple encryption like the WHALE (also a 4096 derivative)
but I do not expect that to be a major problem for the removal
programs.

Since 3k is stolen from the TOM, it is easily detectable with CHKDSK
or MEM or my FreeWare CHKMEM (mine allows use of errorlevels to detect
changes - part of FixUtil5.ZIP on many sites) using the same technique
I developed in 1988 to find the BRAIN. As a consequence, a 640k
machine will report 637k or less (652xxx or less instead of 655360
"total bytes memory" - Please see the FAQ.

Once detected, boot from a clean floppy and infected files will be
seen to have grown.

This points out my personal philosophy for the "safe" PC - Integrity
Management as the first line of defense to detect that "something" has
happened, then the professional tools such as scanners to determine
"what" happened.

					Warmly,
						Padgett

