Date:    Thu, 23 Sep 93 13:15:24 -0400
From:    tegra!vail@uunet.uu.net (Johnathan Vail)
Subject: Re: Flash ROMs

padgett@tccslr.dnet.mmc.com (A. Padgett Peterson) writes:

   >From:    Anthony Naggs <amn@ubik.demon.co.uk>
   >Subject: Flash BIOS (PC)

   >As documented here previously, Intel use Flash memories that include a
   >small 'boot block'.  Like the rest of the BIOS the boot block is
   >programmed at the factory, but it cannot be changed without physically
   >altering the system board, (eg by removing the Flash).

   >Changing the BIOS is done by booting from the "Flash Update Utility"
   >diskette that includes the new BIOS.  The boot block BIOS checks
   >that the new BIOS is for the correct PC model & configuration of
   >equipment, before releasing the interlocks that prevent programming
   >of the Flash.

   >If the boot block BIOS detects an error in the Flash BIOS at boot up,
   >due to deliberate tampering or failure to complete a BIOS update,
   >it will prevent normal use of the system.  The only remedy being to
   >correctly complete installation with the "Flash Update Utility".

   Much though I appreciate Anthony's skill and the Intel people's helpfulness,
   I am afraid that such a scheme is essentially "security by obscurity".
   Agreed, that the "boot block" probably does some very sophisticated
   authentication yet the details *must* be as simple to obtain as disassemblin
g
   the BIOS (and is probably in the near vicinity of the original jump).

True, malevolent code can still spoof the integrity checking but the
"boot block" still provides a known clean way to bring up a machine by
booting from a clean floppy.  This is about the best and only thing
you can do to search for and destroy malevolent code in the flash
parts of the BIOS or on disk.

Isn't that the point, not if the integrity checking can be fooled?

jv

