Date:    Fri, 24 Sep 93 05:36:33 -0400
From:    frisk@complex.is (Fridrik Skulason)
Subject: Anti-virus company distributing viruses ?

There is a rumour going around about some not-entirely-ethical practices
by a certain company in the anti-virus field.  It is possible the rumours
are totally unfounded, or they may be based on the actions of some
over-enthusiastic salesman, actiong without the permission or knowledge of
his superiors.

Anyhow, the story is as follows:

    This company is supposed to have created a collection of files, which
    contain viruses.  However, the viruses have been made "inactive",
    typically by overwriting the beginning of the files with garbage,
    such as "hjgsdhjfg", which makes the programs crash on execution.

    Those files are then given to potential customers, for "testing"
    purposes.

If this rumour is true, I have a serious problem with this.

First, they are spreading viruses - even if they cannot be executed directly,
somebody could extract them from the files.  I, and many other CARO members
have a firm policy of refusing to co-operate with companies that give viruses
to customers.

Second, the scanner produced by this company is able to find the virus code,
but many other products will not find anything, because of the way the
viruses have been modified.  I do not trust, and will not co-operate with
a company engaging in dishonest marketing practices.

Now, I do not know if this rumour is true, but if anybody can confirm this,
I (and others) would be very much interested in hearing about it.

- -frisk

