Date:    Wed, 22 Sep 93 20:21:50 -0400
From:    "Roger Riordan" <riordan@tmxmelb.mhs.oz.au>
Subject: Re: Loren virus (PC)

nickless@ccs.carleton.ca wrote:

>Our Physics Dept. here at Carleton University has been hit by the Loren
>virus. The virus was distributed via an NFS network and has apparently hit
>all attached network workstations infecting numerous .com and .exe files.

>Apparently, this virus, if left alone long enough, will format your hard
>drive.

Loren infects all .COM and .EXE files opened for execution and all files
referenced by Int 21 fn 11 and 12, which are obsolete commands still used by
the DIR command.  Thus, if the virus is in memory, using DIR will infect all
COM and .EXE files opened.  The virus hides increases in file length when
active in memory.

The virus counts the number of files infected, and if the counter reaches 20
the warhead is triggered.  This tries to format cylinder 0, head 0 on
drive C.  If this fails, it tries drives A and B.  If it suceeds in
formatting any drive the following message is put to screen:

	Your disk is formatted by the LOREN virus.
	Written by Nguyen Huu Giap.
	Le Hong Phong School *** 8-3-1992

and the counter is reset.  A low level format will usually be needed to
recover affected hard disks.

CYBEC's VET anti-viral software detects and removes the Loren virus.

