Date:    Thu, 23 Sep 93 04:06:45 -0400
From:    frisk@complex.is (Fridrik Skulason)
Subject: Re: Experiments with mutated viruses. (PC)

amn@ubik.demon.co.uk (Anthony Naggs) writes:

>If Dr Solomon's Toolkit failed to detect your 'mutations' it seems
>likely that you destroyed the ability of your viruses to replicate.

Not necessarily.  Because of the way Alan's FINDVIRU works, it is much more
sensitive to modified viruses than may other scanners, including my own F-PROT.
In partucular this means that if you modify the source code to a virus, and
re-assemble it, FINDVIRU may miss it as certain bytes are no longer located
at the offsets it expects.  F-PROT does not depend on location information,
that is, if the virus still contains the original search string, it will be
found, even if the search string is located at a different offset.

>I do not understand why you have performed your "mutation detection
>experiment",

Probably to test how likely a scanner is to detect a randomly modified virus...
after all, for every new virus written fgrom scratch, there are 2 or 3 that
are created by modifying older viruses.

- -frisk

