Date:    Thu, 23 Sep 93 07:35:03 -0400
From:    vfreak@aol.com
Subject: Bait files (PC)

>I observe increasing reference to the use of "bait files" as a means
>to detect virus activity. What more specifically are bait files? What
>characteristics do bait files have that make them more succulent and
>desirable to ALL viruses (including unknown viruses) than juicy, fat,
>frequently-used application programs or operating system executables?

Bait files are on the same premise of tying a goat to a stake in the ground
in hopes that a predator will come by for a snack. When the predator comes to
eat the goatm the predator getstraped or killed.

Bait files are usually small do nothing programs for viruses to attach to..

I would rather have a virus attached to a 1-10 K bait file than have a
specimen attached to a 50 - 200K file in my collection. Besides since users
know exactly what is supposed to be in their bait files, it is much easier to
know where the virus is located, and easier to study.

Bill

