Date:    Thu, 23 Sep 93 11:58:02 -0400
From:    padgett@tccslr.dnet.mmc.com (A. Padgett Peterson)
Subject: Satan-Bug (PC)

This is not a particularly interesting virus however several elements have
expressed concern so some description is advisable.

The major problem is that while the virus is very easy to detect when resident
on a PC (my sample steals 9k from the Top of Memory - see the FAQ), the
polymorphic encryption makes it difficult to remove from a file once infected
(why good backups are always a good idea).

If you are concerned, my FreeWare CHKMEM (part of FixUtil5) will detect
it when resident even if you do not know how much memory a PC is supposed to
have so is usable as part of AUTOEXEC.BAT (since the virus goes after
COMMAND.COM first) or a LAN login script. It does not hide any better than
the 4096 did three years ago (and makes the same mistakes).

Further, normal LAN defenses will protect servers and prevent spread that
way, the virus does not use any special LAN-aware code for this.

The major problem is that anti-virus programs relying on validation code
attached to executable files may find it stripped off. Those that permit
execution without errors when this happens have only themselves to blame.

Finally, I have seen some unfounded rumors that the virus was directed
against government machines. This is not true. IMHO it is just another
sloppily written virus that is more annoying than most, is easy to detect,
and should not spread very far (unless it "gets lucky" 8*(

							Warmly,
								Padgett

