Date:    Thu, 23 Sep 93 12:25:04 -0400
From:    Otto Stolz <RZOTTO@NYX.UNI-KONSTANZ.DE>
Subject: Re: Stoned virus , need disinfector (PC)

On Thu, 09 Sep 93 12:57:43 -0400 B. Wirth <wirth@NADC.NADC.NAVY.MIL>
said:
> [...] F-prot v2.09 states that the MBR can not be found be found on
> the second drive (Drive D:).

As was explained before, Stoned is an MBR infector, and there is only
one MBR per hard drive, that is not part of any partition.

If you do not want to bother with these finer points, use the /HARD
parameter when invoking F-Prot; this tells the program to inspect the
whole hard disk (i.e. 1 MBR, and all partitions) for viruses.

On Fri, 10 Sep 93 08:55:23 -0400 Fergus Somers <fergus@odyssey.ucc.ie>
said:
> Does anyone know of a site where I can my hands on a disinfector for
> the stoned virus (on a floppy disk at least). [...]

Yes, your nearest Computer Shop: the product you need is marketed as
"MS-DOS 5.0" (or later versions). You may even have it already got :-)
See below for the detailed procedures.

Before you start you have to plan your action along the following lines:

1. With a reliable scanner, check all Computers you are in charge for.
   Remove the virus from their hard disks (see below). Make sure that
   no unchecked floppy disks are used in these computers (cf. step 3,
   below) -- if necessary even by locking the disk drives, or the
   keyboards, until you have completed the whole action.

2. Collect all floppy disks that were used in any computers found
   infected in step 1. It is essential that you really find all those
   disks, so hunt them down in all conceivable and inconceivable
   places: in cupbourds and drawers, in pockets and bags, don't over-
   look even those that are abused as rulers or saucers!

3. With a reliable scanner, check all disks collected in step 2. Take
   notes which ones are infected, and remove the virus from them (see
   below).

4. Find out on which computers the disks found infected in step 2 were
   used. Notify the people in charge for those computers and make them
   repeat the whole procedure (including the painful step 4!) for these
   computers.

5. Protect all computers you ar in charge for from re-infection.

Removal from hard disks:

As Stoned is an MBR infector that leaves the Partition Table in place,
you can use the FDISK command of MS-DOS 5.0 (and up) to write a new,
uninfected, MBR to the hard disk. I recommend the following procedure:

1. Switch off your computer (Cntrl-Alt-Del is *not* appropriate), then
   boot from a clean DOS 5.0 diskette. Deny any offer to install the
   system on the hard disk. Invoke any commands desired to make you
   feel comfortable, such as KEYB GR, or PROMPT $P$G.

2. Make sure the partition table is in place by
   FDISK /STATUS
   DIR C:
   DIR D:      ((if there is a D partition on the disk))

3. Only if step 2 proves undisturbed access to the hard disk, enter
   FDISK /MBR

4. Run your favourite virus scanner from the floppy disk to check the
   hard disk.

5. Switch off the computer, then boot from the hard disk.

This procedure uses only the hardware of the computer; hence it will work
regardless of the operating system you are normally using.

Removal from floppy disks:

On floppy disks, there is no MBR; Stoned uses the DOS-BR instead. There
are two commands in standard DOS to replace the DOS-BR:
- - SYS    (which works only for bootable disks, and requires the very
         DOS version that is on the disk),
- - FORMAT (which will erase all data that are on the disk).

You can use the following generic DOS procedure to remove Stoned (and
most MBR and DOS-BR infectors) from a couple of data disks:

0. Use a clean computer (see above), otherwise you will infect every
   disk you are trying to clean.

1. Format a supply of floppy disks.

2. Copy the data from an infected disk to a clean disk prepared in step
   1, using the XCOPY command, or equivalent. Check if copy is complete.
   Repeat for all disks.

3. FORMAT the infected disks, and use them for other purposes.

Good luck,
