Date:    Thu, 23 Sep 93 17:36:53 +0400
From:    "Dmitry O. Gryaznov" <grdo@grdo.botik.yaroslavl.su>
Subject: Re: Viruses and Ctrl-Break (PC)

    Mikko Hypponen writes:

>While analysing viruses, I've noted that during the infection routine
>many of them turn off both DOS critical error handler and Ctrl-Break
>checking.
>
>It is obvious why the critical error messages are suppressed,
>but I can't figure out why to disable Ctrl-Break. Viruses that disable
>Ctrl-Break checking include at least Phoenix.800, TPE.1_0.Girafe and
>Hidenowt.
>
>Does anybody have any idea about why they're doing it?

Not only listed viruses, but dozens more do the same thing. The reason?
It's obvious: in order not to be interrupted while calling DOS functions.
Otherwise a user might (accidentally) stop the infection process by
pressing Ctrl-Break.
